In this CAREER award, the PI investigated nonlinear mechanics stemming from contact interfaces and its influence on structural dynamics. Mechanical testing were conducted across length scales ranging from microns to centimeters on various contact interfaces. Materials tested also ranged from very soft and multiphasic materials such as fluid-imbibed foams to structural metals such as steel and aluminum alloys. Both transient and forced responses of systems with contact interfaces were measured and related to the interfacial mechanics. Numerical and analytical models of interfaces validated by experimental observations lead to several key contributions to mechanics and structural dynamics fields:

Broadband damping can be achieved by contact interfaces as long as the contact resonances are tuned to the relaxation response of the bulk materials. This phenomenon was commonly observed in biological and bio-inspired materials, and enabled the PI to develop a passive broadband damper;

Constitutive nonlinearities influence contact response significantly in elastoviscoplastic materials, and thus contact nonlinearities are difficult to infer solely from quasistatic loading/unloading experiments;   

Combination of transient and forced responses of dynamic mechanical testers enable accurate characterization of contact slip, peeling, stiffness and damping nonlinearities;

Structural internal resonances can be triggered selectively by contact slip and peeling, and thus analyses of internally-resonant structural responses promote nondesctructive evaluation of contact interfaces; 

Scalable and sustainable surface patterning is possible through natural phase decomposition and elastic-fluidic instabilities; yet, such surface patterns would always exhibit randomness in pattern topography and hence recruit broad ranges of length scales and deliver high stress concentration factors and potential failure in dynamic contact applications.   



Most of those research findings were presented in international conferences, and engineering and science exhibitions on campus. Besides the research output, the project enabled the PI to implement active learning modules to mechanics and vibrations curriculum. The graduate students who participated in the project received training on advanced experimental and numerical tools such as microscale indentation and scratch testing inside scanning electron microscope, fretting tests at macroscopic length scales, transient and forced shear rheometry, cantilever-beam-based contact testers (e.g., atomic force microscopes, mesoscale tribometers), multipoint laser vibrometry, modal analyses, boundary and finite element methods. 



